    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-03-09T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-03-09T19:00:00-05:00" n="579"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d579">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.00111 Armament Control/1230a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-03-09T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 9, 1937—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>120. Miles M. Sherover,<note n="39a" xml:id="d579fn39a">President of Hanover
                        Sales Corp., 30 Broad St., New York City.</note> acting on behalf of the
                    Spanish Government, entered into a contract in November, 1936, with the Bellanca
                    Aircraft Corporation to purchase 20 single engine planes of a special type
                    powered with Pratt and Whitney engines. The planes were paid for by Sherover
                    with money provided by the Spanish Embassy in Washington. None of the planes had
                    been built, however, before January 8 when the exportation of arms to Spain was
                    prohibited by law. The Hanover Sales Corporation, of which Sherover is
                    President, registered on March 9 as an exporter of arms. Sherover states that he
                    has sold the planes to Air France and that they will be shipped from New York to
                    Havre via the United States Lines in batches of three or four beginning probably
                    on March 17. He states further that he has impressed upon the purchaser that the
                    planes must not be transshipped to Spain.</p>
                <p>These facts are furnished you for your information and such discreet use as you
                    may deem appropriate. Full report follows by pouch.<note n="40"
                        xml:id="d579fn40">Instruction No. 186, March 16; not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
